In October 2018, Starbucks debuted its first U.S. signing store in Washington D.C. The store is located on H Street a few blocks from Gallaudet University, the world’s only university for deaf and hard-of-hearing students. The store employs 24 workers who are all conversant in American Sign Language, and added extra design elements and technology to make it more accessible for deaf people. Customers can communicate in ASL or write their orders on a tech pad. Instead of hearing their name called, customers look up at a screen to see when their drink is ready. The shop follows Starbucks' first international signing store, which opened in Kula Lumpur, Malaysia, in 2016.

Looking for a unique coffee shop with a familiar name? This Capitol Hill Starbucks will do just fine with its setting in an old two story building. Nothing alerts you to the fact it's a chain coffee shop until you see the sign. It even has a bit of a secret area most in a hurry would never know about.  The beautiful Capitol Hill setting with nicely landscaped yards in the surround is part of the reason I elevated to a 4. Its coolness factor screams check me out. The exterior has a patio left of the entrance. The walk up had some minor debris and I noticed rotted wood on the front window that needs attention. Street parking  is in front and limited.  Make no mistake this shop is no secret and on a weekday morning around 8 AM it was slammed!!! They were packed inside and most of the first floor. The interior also has a different feel with high ceilings, drop lighting dark louvre blinds on the windows. All the elements are of course present with merchandise that you're in a Starbucks.  The line moved quickly and I ordered a White Chocolate Mocha in a for here mug with lemon pound cake. My wife a black iced tea. The staff was very busy, but I did conjure up a smile from the staff and the app worked flawlessly.  I sat at the end of the bar and prepared my day of tour of the city. The coffee, cake and tea were out in around 10 minutes. The tea came out ahead. This is longer than I'm accustomed to, but I can let it go. They were busy and Mobil orders were cranking out. I really liked the hustle of the staff. The coffee was up to my specifications since this is my usual. The cake fresh. I enjoyed people watching over my breakfast very much. Movers and shakers, mom's with strollers and tourist all meshed together with a common goal of a caffeine fix.  The secret behind this shop has yet to be revealed. A glorious second floor space that's a must to check out is the locals "secret".. Exposed brick, comfy seating and I beams with a fireplace sound enchanting? A large wooden communal table seats twelve. Windows let the sunshine in, but it's not overbearing opposite the sun. Lots of areas to plug in too! They even offer a walled off private room that easily seats six. The biggest surprise was that it had lots of availability for customers to seek refuge from the craziness below.  I'm a fan of Starbucks and enjoy a cup a few times weekly. This gem of a store stands out as a charmer with its gorgeous setting and second floor space. 3.5, rounding up and recommend.

This Starbucks has a Clover coffee maker and serves a set of the special Reserve coffees, all smooth and highly flavorful.  There are others found in California MD and near Madison Square Garden in NYC.  Clover shops are the only place Reserve coffees may be purchased in small bags. Plan to spend some time with a cup to see if you want a bag. 50 g for 16 oz will approximate the Clover flavor, but the Clover filters out grounds and has uniform brewing time/temp for all the coffee brewed.  Kind of what you might expect for a machine that sold for $10,000 before Starbucks bought the company that made it.  Reserve branded venues may see more Clovers.

My guy and I aren't from the area but were in town for a baseball game and passed this Starbucks on our walk back to the train station. I have Celiac Disease and wasn't sure what Starbucks had to offer that would be safe for me to drink. Upon asking one gentleman at the register about what products are gluten-free, he told me none. I was pretty surprised considering that I know that the coffee itself is gluten free, I just wasn't sure about the mixed coffees/teas incase they came in powder form. I asked him if they had a food allergy list that I could look at and he said 'We used to have one but I don't know where it is.' Fair enough, things can be misplaced. Another male employee making coffee chimed in and asked what the issue was and I told him that I couldn't have gluten and was curious as to what drinks are gluten free. He said 'None, but we have sugar free drinks'. I knew right away after he said that that they had absolutely no idea what gluten was or knew what a gluten allergy entails. Not only were they completely ignorant about an important food allergy while working in a place that sells food and drinks that could be tainted with gluten, but they didn't even try to be helpful or understanding about my situation. I own a small business myself and was shocked at how unaccommodating they were. Thankfully a very knowledgeable and kind young lady named Micha chimed in and gave me the box that the Chai latte mix came in so I could read the ingredients. She explained to them what a gluten allergy was and was extremely helpful and accommodating. She also was nice enough to recommend other local gluten free bakeries and restaurants in the area that I should try out. Her customer service skills were A+ and I feel like she should get a raise or be promoted, something to acknowledge her hard work and kindness. I would have given this review 0 stars if possible due to my experience with the other two employees but I would give Micha a 5 star rating.  As a side note, the store looked clean and we enjoyed their outside patio but my guy said that the bathroom that he went into was filthy and unkept and it almost made him want to gag.
